                <TD valign="top"> <div align="justify"><font FACE="Arial">
                  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">I have worked on 
                  biped locomotion for my university thesis work. The objective 
                  was to design a control strategy that could be implemented on 
                  the quadruped robot Sony ERS-210 (commonly known as AIBO), in 
                  order to let it walk on its hind legs. Being designed for 
                  quadruped gaits, this robot has several limitations which make 
                  biped locomotion a challenging task, such as passive feet, a 
                  high baricenter in the erect posture, and relatively weak 
                  actuators. In view of this, it has been chosen to fully 
                  exploit the double support phase, in which the robot has both 
                  (hind) feet on the&nbsp; ground, in order to achieve the 
                  correct take-off conditions for performing the single support 
                  phase. During the latter, the motion of the mechanism is 
                  essentially uncontrolled but can be predicted and planned in 
                  advance using a simple equivalent mechanical scheme. Details 
                  of this work, as well as simulation and experimental results 
                  can be obtained at</font><font FACE="Arial" COLOR="#0000ff">
                  </font><font FACE="Arial">my <a href="bipedloc.htm">Biped 
                  Locomotion</a> web page.</p>
                  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">I continued this 
                  work during my first year of PHD studying, and the successful 
                  results were published and illustrated in the ICRA conference 
                  (<a href="files/ArticleAIBOBiped.pdf">download the article</a>). 
                  I have also worked on quadruped locomotion, and I have 
                  designed and implemented the omni-directional walking 
                  generator for the robot ERS-210, that is currently being used 
                  by the &quot;SPQR&quot; robot team of the University of Rome in the 
                  RoboCup competitions. The main advantage of 
                  omni-directionality is that it is possible to freely assign 
                  both a linear and a rotational velocity to the robot, so it is 
                  able to walk in every direction while at the same time 
                  rotating on itself. This has proved extremely important, 
                  because many problems such as motion planning, obstacle 
                  avoidance, ball tracking have become much easier and more 
                  accuratevafter the introduction of such walking generator.</p>
                  </font>&nbsp;</div></TD>
